From: btalley@spot.wrc.xerox.com (Brian Talley spot 0102-06a)
Subject: Re: Handbook 486 and Linux
Date: Thu, 2 Dec 1993 21:19:33 GMT

In article <1993Dec01.204743.29420@taylor.wyvern.com> mark@taylor.wyvern.com (Mark A. Davis) writes:
>shmueli@twain.ucs.umass.edu (Avinoam Shmueli ( Avi )) writes:
>
>>Liz Stokes posted on 1 Dec 1993 11:07:07 -0500:
>>  | should be). I haven't gotten X configured yet - more notes to follow when I
>>  | do. I periodically get error messages "Unexpected HD interrupt" - I'm not
>>  | sure what causes it, but it doesn't seem to cause any harm, the machine
>>  | keeps right on going. 
>
>>Liz, thanks for all the info: it's very reassuring to know SLS
>>installs; I'm considering a portable myself and that is an issue.
>>PLEASE post your Xconfig with the LCD screen, if you (and the screen
>>:-( )survive the setup procedure: I wish you good luck!
>
>>I'm nervous to hear about the resume problem, though...
>
>Yes, thank you.  I have been considering a handbook myself.  The pricing is
>still kind of steep, and I also have been wondering very much about the
>resume and X myself.  Also been wondering about battery life running Linux
>(I assumed that some of the power saving options would not work properly
> under a REAL OS, or perhaps be too annoying).
>
>Please do keep us informed of your progress!!! :)

I have a HandBook 486DX2/40 myself (just got it two days ago). It runs
Linux very well, and X works fine.  Suspend and resume features work
flawlessly on my machine (don't know what's different about mine versus
Liz's HB).  I have experienced no hangs or crashings as a result of
using suspend/resume (in fact, I have experienced no hangs or crashings,
period).

Anyone who would like a copy of my Xconfig may have one - just send
me mail.

The system is quick, the display is slow (as one would expect), the
EZ-Point pointing device is nice, but takes a bit of getting used to.
Battery life seems good: ~2 hours average with no PM, several hours
with PM.  I find it ideal for use as a demo system, something to take
notes on in meetings, and for general use at home and work.

My only complaint is that GW used a display with an odd aspect ratio,
causing everything to appear "squashed".  The display is still quite
usable, IMO, but I would have preferred if it were a bit smaller with
a "correct" 4:3 aspect ratio.

If anyone would like any more info, feel free to send me email.

Now, if someone has any info on PCMCIA support for Linux they'd like
to share, I'd be extremely grateful!

--Brian
__________
Brian Talley, Systems Consultant, Xerox Corporation, Rochester, New York
btalley@spectrum.wrc.xerox.com


