From: pawel@cs.ualberta.ca (Pawel Gburzynski)
Subject: Re: Adaptec 154xC + disks > 1GB
Date: Thu, 2 Dec 1993 19:22:21 GMT

fox@graphics.cs.nyu.edu (David Fox) writes:

>In article <1993Dec2.021932.22252@cs.UAlberta.CA> pawel@cs.UAlberta.CA (Pawel Gburzynski) writes:

>] I wonder if the people who maintain SCSI-HOWTO could add a note
>] saying that AHA154xC and AHA154xCF is not going to work with disks
>] larger than 1GB.

>I use an adaptec 1542C with a seagate 42100 1.8 gigabyte
>disk with no difficulty.  Earlier versions of ext2 couldn't
>create partitions over 1 gigabyte, but I don't need 
>partitions over 1 gigabyte.

I have received a number of replies from people whose 1542C`s work fine with
disks > 1GB. Sorry for the confusion, but then there must be at least two
different types of the 1542C (which makes the confusion even worse). In
particular, what was the problem discussed by Eric Youngdale in the following
posting?

=======================

In article <2cqvu1$btn@grouper.mkt.csd.harris.com> srp@rcx1 (Stephen Pietrowicz)
 writes:
>I'm posting this for a friend:
>
>I received the message "aha1542.c interrupt received, but no mail" while
>trying to install the Yggdrasil Linux on a system with an Adaptec 1542B
>SCSI adapter.  The failure happens with the most current Adaptec
>microcode and BIOS ROMs.  Older 1542s do not have this problem.  I
>switched back to my old ROMs (maybe Rev 1.1, circa 1990) and I was
>able to install Linux without a hitch.
>
>If someone is interested in fixing the aha1542.c driver, Adaptec at
>(408) 945-8600 will send you a free replacement pair of ROMs (P/N
>528600 Rev D), along with the updated v3.0a software kit "ASPI MS-DOS
>Manager with ASPI Disk Module" (P/N 527800-01 Rev B) - all for no
>charge at all.  Just explain that you want to use greater-than-
>one-gig drives on your 1542.

..................

        The problem is that with the >1Gb roms in the controller, you need to
send some special command to "unlock" the thing.  As far as I can tell, this is
just a magic command that you use so as to tell the controller that yes we
really understand that you have the >1Gb ROM.  Without this special command you
get the "Interrupt received, but no mail" message, and the controller is
unusable.  All of the documentation that I have read suggests that Adaptec does
not recommend that you use the >1Gb roms on a non-DOS system.  Also, none of
the technical reference manuals (either for the 1542 or the 174x) explain what
is needed.  I have sent email to an Adaptec developer asking them about this,
and my queries have been ignored.  For now, my position is that since this is
apparently an unsupported configuration as far as Adaptec is concerned, I am
not interested in trying to patch the 1542 driver to try and use the extended
mapping.

        If someone can convince me that Adaptec does support extended mapping
with various forms of unix, *and* they can pry the relevant technical details
out of the hands of Adaptec (no mean feat), I would consider patching the
driver to make use of this.  I am not interested in spending a lot of time on
the phone arguing with Adaptec myself.

>The new ROMs support "extended translation," which bypasses MS-DOS's
>limit of 1024 cylinders by changing the cylinder granularity from
>one meg to eight megs.

        Yes, I know all of this.  You should not use these ROMs with linux.


==========================

Apparently, I have the wrong ROMs and this can happen to anybody.


